"""
mkt-christ fill — 1 Kings ch22
Covers: 51 missing verses (1-13, 15-33, 35-53; vv14 and 34 already present)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-1kings-22-fill.py

Key typological decisions:
- 400 false prophets vs. 1 true prophet (Micaiah) = loneliness of prophetic truth
- Heavenly council vision (vv19-23) = prophetic access to the divine council
- The lying spirit = divine sovereignty and the hardening of the self-deceived
- Ahab's disguise = the coward king hiding from judgment; cf. Adam hiding from God
- Random arrow (v34, already present) = judgment finds the hidden
- Dogs licking Ahab's blood (v38) = exact fulfillment of Elijah's 21:19 prophecy
- Ahaziah begins (vv51-53) = dynasty of apostasy perpetuated
"""

import json
import pathlib

def load_comm(path):
    p = pathlib.Path(path)
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(path, data):
    pathlib.Path(path).write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2))

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
"22": {
"1": "<p>Three years pass without war between Israel and Syria after the treaty of ch20. The narrative pause &#8212; three years of quiet following Ahab&#8217;s covenantal failure &#8212; is the calm before the judgment that will arrive in this chapter. Prophetic fulfillment does not always come immediately; deferred judgment can look like security. Christ&#8217;s parable of the fig tree given one more year (Luke 13:6&#8211;9) captures the same dynamic: patience is not cancellation, and the tree that does not bear fruit in the extended time will be cut down.</p>",
"2": "<p>Jehoshaphat king of Judah comes down to the king of Israel &#8212; the first formal encounter between the Davidic southern king and the apostate northern king. Jehoshaphat&#8217;s willingness to visit Ahab, and the royal alliance it signals, will be the subject of sustained prophetic critique. The danger of covenant people aligning with those who have abandoned the covenant &#8212; even for apparently strategic reasons &#8212; is a persistent warning in the prophets (Isa 30:1&#8211;2; 2 Cor 6:14).</p>",
"3": "<p>Ahab tells his servants that Ramoth-Gilead belongs to Israel and should be recovered from the Syrians. The king&#8217;s territorial claim is legitimate &#8212; Ramoth was an Israelite city of refuge &#8212; but the way the claim will be pursued reveals the character beneath the policy. Legitimate goals pursued through faithless means still produce faithless outcomes. The Messiah&#8217;s kingdom comes not by territorial recovery through alliances but through the cross (John 18:36).</p>",
"4": "<p>Ahab asks Jehoshaphat to join the campaign against Ramoth-Gilead. Jehoshaphat&#8217;s reply &#8212; &lsquo;I am as you are, my people as your people, my horses as your horses&rsquo; &#8212; is the formula of covenant merger, the same words Ruth speaks to Naomi (Ruth 1:16) in the context of covenant loyalty. Here the formula is borrowed and misapplied: Jehoshaphat&#8217;s total identification with Ahab will nearly cost him his life and earns a rebuke from the prophet Jehu (2 Chr 19:2).</p>",
"5": "<p>Jehoshaphat&#8217;s condition: &lsquo;Inquire first for the word of the LORD.&rsquo; The request to seek YHWH&#8217;s word before battle is proper covenant practice (cf. Num 27:21; Josh 9:14). But the form of inquiry is about to be corrupted: 400 prophets will answer with what the king wants to hear. The form of piety &#8212; asking for a word &#8212; without the substance of genuine openness to correction is one of the more subtle forms of using God&#8217;s name to authorize self-will.</p>",
"6": "<p>Ahab assembles 400 prophets who speak with one voice: &lsquo;Go up, for the Lord will give it into the hand of the king.&rsquo; The 400 form the court prophetic apparatus &#8212; the religious establishment aligned with royal policy. Their unanimity is suspicious: genuine prophetic witness rarely achieves unanimity on specific military questions. The contrast with the 7,000 who had not bowed to Baal (19:18) is instructive &#8212; the institutional prophets are not the same as the hidden remnant.</p>",
"7": "<p>Jehoshaphat asks: &lsquo;Is there not here another prophet of YHWH of whom we may inquire?&rsquo; His discernment &#8212; that 400 unanimous voices do not constitute a genuine word of YHWH &#8212; is remarkable in context. Jehoshaphat recognizes that genuine prophetic voices are sometimes scarce and that institutional consensus is not the same as divine word. The NT&rsquo;s warning that false prophets will come &lsquo;in sheep&#8217;s clothing&rsquo; (Matt 7:15) requires exactly this kind of discernment.</p>",
"8": "<p>Ahab admits there is one &#8212; Micaiah son of Imlah &#8212; but adds &lsquo;I hate him, for he never prophesies good concerning me, but always evil.&rsquo; The admission reveals the entire situation: Ahab knows there is a true prophet, knows the man will speak YHWH&#8217;s word rather than royal preference, and despises him for it. The preference for comfortable prophecy over true prophecy (2 Tim 4:3: &lsquo;people will not endure sound teaching&rsquo;) is not innocent ignorance but deliberate choice.</p>",
"9": "<p>A eunuch goes to fetch Micaiah. The royal court&#8217;s access to the true prophet &#8212; he is reachable, he is known, he is not in hiding &#8212; makes Ahab&#8217;s habitual suppression of his word all the more culpable. Micaiah is not a marginal figure unknown to the court; he is a recognized prophet whom the king refuses to consult. Willful avoidance of available truth is the structure of all deliberate unbelief.</p>",
"10": "<p>Ahab and Jehoshaphat sit on their thrones at the threshing floor near the gate of Samaria, with all the prophets prophesying before them. The royal pageant &#8212; two kings enthroned, 400 prophets performing &#8212; is staged spectacle designed to produce a predetermined result. The threshing floor as the site of this false inquiry is ironic: threshing floors are sites of judgment throughout the OT (Hos 9:1&#8211;2; Ruth 3; the threshing floor of Araunah where David&#8217;s plague stopped). The kings seek confirmation; the floor will be a site of judgment.</p>",
"11": "<p>Zedekiah son of Chenaanah makes iron horns and declares: &lsquo;Thus says YHWH: With these you shall push the Syrians until they are destroyed.&rsquo; The dramatic prop &#8212; iron horns &#8212; adds performative authority to the false prophecy. The symbolic action is the right form (prophets regularly enacted their messages) with the wrong content. False religion mimics the forms of true religion while emptying them of covenantal substance. The test is not the performance but the conformity to YHWH&#8217;s word.</p>",
"12": "<p>All the prophets prophesy the same thing: &lsquo;Go up to Ramoth-Gilead and triumph; YHWH will give it into the king&#8217;s hand.&rsquo; The collective utterance of the false prophets &#8212; unanimous, confident, specific &#8212; has the form of prophetic certainty. Against this wall of institutional consensus, one man will stand. Christ himself faced the same structure: the religious establishment&#8217;s unanimous condemnation of him was wrong, and the one dissenting voice (John 19:12 &#8212; Pilate&#8217;s reluctance) was insufficient against the mob&#8217;s unanimity.</p>",
"13": "<p>The messenger who goes for Micaiah urges him: &lsquo;Look, the words of the prophets with one accord are favorable to the king. Let your word be like the word of one of them, and speak favorably.&rsquo; The social pressure on Micaiah &#8212; align with the consensus for your own good &#8212; is the pressure every true prophetic voice faces. Jeremiah&#8217;s complaint (Jer 20:9: &lsquo;If I say I will not mention him&#8230; there is in my heart something like a burning fire&rsquo;) names the cost of prophetic integrity that Micaiah will bear.</p>",
"15": "<p>Micaiah&#8217;s first answer &#8212; &lsquo;Go up and triumph; YHWH will give it into the hand of the king&rsquo; &#8212; is the ironic echo of the false prophets&#8217; answer. Ahab immediately recognizes the parody: &lsquo;How many times shall I make you swear that you speak to me nothing but the truth in the name of YHWH?&rsquo; The king who has forbidden himself the truth now demands it when the performance is too transparent. Truth becomes interesting to the self-deceived only when the parody of it makes them uncomfortable.</p>",
"16": "<p>Ahab&#8217;s demand: &lsquo;How many times shall I make you swear that you speak to me nothing but the truth in the name of YHWH?&rsquo; The irony is complete: the king who has spent this chapter arranging for comfortable prophecy now demands the truth from the one prophet he hates. The moment of self-awareness &#8212; recognizing that the performed consensus was hollow &#8212; is the edge of repentance that Ahab approaches but will not cross. The truth is available to the last; the tragedy is the choice not to receive it.</p>",
"17": "<p>&lsquo;I saw all Israel scattered on the mountains, as sheep that have no shepherd.&rsquo; Micaiah&#8217;s true prophecy of Ahab&#8217;s death is delivered in pastoral imagery: leaderless sheep on the mountains, each returning home in peace &#8212; peace through the king&#8217;s death rather than through victory. Christ is the Good Shepherd who gives his life for the sheep (John 10:11); Ahab is the bad shepherd whose death scatters the flock. The scattered-sheep imagery will become central to Christ&#8217;s own passion narrative (Matt 26:31: &lsquo;I will strike the shepherd, and the sheep of the flock will be scattered&rsquo;).</p>",
"18": "<p>Ahab to Jehoshaphat: &lsquo;Did I not tell you that he would not prophesy good concerning me, but evil?&rsquo; The king&#8217;s response to Micaiah&#8217;s true word is not engagement with its content but self-referential confirmation: he was right about Micaiah, Micaiah is his enemy, and the prophecy confirms the enmity. The refusal to engage the content of prophetic warning in favor of judging the messenger&#8217;s motives is the final form of self-insulation against the word of God.</p>",
"19": "<p>&lsquo;I saw YHWH sitting on his throne, and all the host of heaven standing beside him on his right hand and on his left.&rsquo; Micaiah&#8217;s vision of the divine council is one of the rare OT glimpses of the heavenly court &#8212; parallel to Isaiah&#8217;s throne vision (Isa 6) and Ezekiel&#8217;s chariot (Ezek 1). The prophet&#8217;s access to the heavenly court is the basis of his authority: he speaks not from observation of earthly conditions but from what he has seen in the council of YHWH (Jer 23:18). Christ is the one whose origin is the council itself (John 1:1; 8:38).</p>",
"20": "<p>YHWH asks the heavenly council: &lsquo;Who will entice Ahab to go up and fall at Ramoth-Gilead?&rsquo; The scene raises deep theological questions about divine sovereignty and deception. What is clear is that the divine council scene frames Ahab&#8217;s fate as already determined &#8212; not arbitrarily but as the judgment upon a king who has persistently refused the truth. The hardening that comes from repeated refusal of the true word is itself a form of divine judgment (cf. Pharaoh, Rom 9:17&#8211;18).</p>",
"21": "<p>&lsquo;Then a spirit came forward and stood before YHWH, saying, I will entice him.&rsquo; The spirit&#8217;s volunteer is the narrative mechanism by which Ahab&#8217;s self-chosen path &#8212; preferring lies &#8212; is brought to its logical end. The relationship between divine sovereignty and human culpability (the Syrians freely attack; Ahab freely disguises himself; the archer freely shoots) is not resolved here but held in tension. Scripture consistently presents judgment as both divinely purposed and humanly deserved.</p>",
"22": "<p>&lsquo;YHWH said to him, By what means? And he said, I will go out and be a lying spirit in the mouth of all his prophets.&rsquo; The lying spirit&#8217;s method &#8212; working through the already-false prophets &#8212; is not the introduction of deception into neutral hearts but the confirmation of the direction the prophets have already chosen. Those who have already chosen to prophesy what the king wants to hear are now given over to the full expression of that choice. The strong delusion of 2 Thess 2:11&#8211;12 operates the same way.</p>",
"23": "<p>&lsquo;And YHWH has put a lying spirit in the mouth of all these your prophets.&rsquo; Micaiah announces the divine verdict to the king&#8217;s face: the 400 prophets are speaking deception, and YHWH himself has purposed their deception as the instrument of the king&#8217;s judgment. This direct declaration &#8212; naming the deception, naming its divine source, naming the king as its target &#8212; is the final prophetic word to Ahab. The gospel&#8217;s offer is the inverse: YHWH purposes the truth, speaks through faithful witnesses, and calls the hearer to life.</p>",
"24": "<p>Zedekiah strikes Micaiah on the cheek: &lsquo;How did the Spirit of YHWH go from me to speak to you?&rsquo; The false prophet strikes the true prophet &#8212; the same gesture as those who struck Christ during his trial (Matt 26:67: &lsquo;Then they spat in his face and struck him&rsquo;). The act of violence against prophetic truth is the invariable response of institutional religion when its false security is exposed. Those who strike the prophets will ultimately stand condemned by the word they tried to silence.</p>",
"25": "<p>Micaiah&#8217;s reply to Zedekiah: &lsquo;Behold, you shall see on that day when you go into an inner chamber to hide yourself.&rsquo; The counter-prophecy is precise: when events unfold, Zedekiah will find himself hiding &#8212; the false prophet exposed by history, seeking concealment. The reference to &lsquo;an inner chamber&rsquo; (<em>ḥeder b&#277;ḥāḏer</em>) echoes the hiding imagery throughout Kings: those who manipulate events for survival will still need to hide. There is no hiding from the prophetic word&#8217;s fulfillment.</p>",
"26": "<p>Ahab orders Micaiah imprisoned: &lsquo;Put this fellow in prison and feed him with meager bread and water until I come in peace.&rsquo; The imprisonment of the true prophet is the last act of the king who prefers comfortable lies to dangerous truth. The NT pattern &#8212; John the Baptist imprisoned by Herod; Paul imprisoned by Felix &#8212; inhabits the same dynamic. The king&#8217;s power to imprison the prophet is real but temporary; the prophet&#8217;s word outlasts the prison.</p>",
"27": "<p>&lsquo;Feed him with meager bread and water until I come in peace.&rsquo; Ahab&#8217;s conditional &#8212; &lsquo;until I come in peace&rsquo; &#8212; ties Micaiah&#8217;s release to a military victory that will not come. The king has, in effect, sealed Micaiah&#8217;s fate by the condition: if Ahab falls at Ramoth-Gilead as prophesied, no king will return to release Micaiah. Ahab&#8217;s confidence in his own survival is the final expression of his refusal of the prophetic word.</p>",
"28": "<p>Micaiah&#8217;s last word: &lsquo;If you return in peace, YHWH has not spoken by me.&rsquo; Then, addressing the assembled people: &lsquo;Hear, all you peoples!&rsquo; The prophetic challenge to public verification &#8212; let the outcome test the word &#8212; is the standard of Deut 18:21&#8211;22. Micaiah&#8217;s appeal to the people is his last prophetic act: even if the king will not hear, the record must be public. The incarnate Word similarly placed himself before the public for judgment (John 18:20: &lsquo;I have spoken openly to the world&#8217;).</p>",
"29": "<p>Ahab and Jehoshaphat go up to Ramoth-Gilead. The king&#8217;s decision to proceed despite Micaiah&#8217;s prophecy is the final act of Ahab&#8217;s self-destruction. He has heard the truth, dismissed it, imprisoned its bearer, and now acts on the lie. Every opportunity for repentance has been refused; the narrative now simply records the outworking of the refused word. The road to Ramoth-Gilead is not a strategic error; it is the deliberate choice of the lie over the truth at every opportunity.</p>",
"30": "<p>Ahab proposes to disguise himself for battle while Jehoshaphat wears his robes. The royal disguise &#8212; hiding identity to avoid the prophesied judgment &#8212; echoes Adam hiding from YHWH in the garden (Gen 3:8). No human disguise conceals from divine judgment. Jehoshaphat&#8217;s agreement to wear the royal robes is dangerous: his identity as the visibly-robed king will make him the target of Syrian commanders who are explicitly ordered to kill the king of Israel (v31). Ahab&#8217;s plan endangers his ally while protecting himself.</p>",
"31": "<p>The king of Syria commands his thirty-two chariot commanders: &lsquo;Fight with neither small nor great, but only with the king of Israel.&rsquo; The precise targeting of the Israelite king makes Ahab&#8217;s disguise the key tactical question. The Syrian commanders&#8217; instruction to target only the king of Israel mirrors the demonic targeting of the seed of the woman throughout redemptive history &#8212; the attack focused on the covenant king. In Ahab&#8217;s case, the targeted king is hiding behind his ally.</p>",
"32": "<p>The chariot commanders see Jehoshaphat in his royal robes and think he is the king of Israel &#8212; they turn to fight him. The trap Ahab has set for his ally springs: the false robes bring the enemy upon Jehoshaphat. Jehoshaphat cries out (2 Chr 18:31 says he cried to YHWH, and YHWH helped him). The man who wore the wrong king&#8217;s robes is delivered; the man who wore the disguise will be struck. The irony is complete: the hidden king dies; the visible king escapes.</p>",
"33": "<p>When the chariot commanders see that Jehoshaphat is not the king of Israel, they turn back from pursuing him. The recognition of the wrong target saves Jehoshaphat. But the misdirection that saved Jehoshaphat is the same misdirection that condemned Ahab: the false king (the disguised Ahab) was not identifiable to the commanders. What saves Jehoshaphat is precisely the failure of identification; what condemns Ahab is that the failure of human identification does not fail divine judgment &#8212; the random arrow finds him anyway (v34).</p>",
"35": "<p>The battle continues; Ahab is propped up in his chariot facing the Syrians, the blood of his wound flowing into the bottom of the chariot, and he dies at evening. The death of the disguised king &#8212; held upright by royal dignity even as his blood drains away &#8212; is the chapter&#8217;s tragic image. Ahab does not flee; he stays in his chariot facing the battle. The dignity in his dying does not retroactively validate his life&#8217;s pattern of apostasy, but the narrative records it without contempt. Even the condemned deserve to die with some dignity in their station.</p>",
"36": "<p>At sunset a cry passes through the army: &lsquo;Every man to his city, and every man to his country.&rsquo; Micaiah&#8217;s prophecy of Israel scattered like sheep without a shepherd (v17) is fulfilled in real time: the leaderless army disperses, each man returning home. The prophetic word given in the morning is enacted by evening. The speed of fulfillment &#8212; prophecy given that very day, fulfilled that day &#8212; collapses the distance between word and event to make the verification undeniable.</p>",
"37": "<p>The king dies and is brought to Samaria &#8212; buried there in accordance with the custom. The king who had planned to enter Ramoth-Gilead in triumph enters Samaria in death. The contrast between the anticipated return in peace and the actual return as a corpse is the judgment on all confident plans that override prophetic warning. The wisdom of Prov 19:21 &#8212; &lsquo;Many are the plans in the mind of a man, but it is the purpose of the LORD that will stand&rsquo; &#8212; finds its narrative embodiment here.</p>",
"38": "<p>They wash the chariot by the pool of Samaria; the dogs lick up his blood, and the prostitutes washed themselves there &#8212; according to the word of YHWH which he had spoken. Elijah&#8217;s prophecy in 21:19 &#8212; &lsquo;the dogs shall lick your blood, even yours&rsquo; &#8212; is fulfilled in detail. The precision of prophetic fulfillment &#8212; the specific location (Samaria&#8217;s pool), the specific agency (dogs), the specific substance (blood) &#8212; authenticates the prophetic word and the God who spoke it. Every detail of messianic prophecy fulfilled in Christ operates by the same principle of precise correspondence.</p>",
"39": "<p>The rest of Ahab&#8217;s acts &#8212; the ivory house and all the cities he built &#8212; are in the book of the chronicles of the kings of Israel. The regnal summary formula closes Ahab&#8217;s account with his architectural achievements. The ivory house represents the wealth accumulated during his reign; it is the permanent record of what was built while the covenant was being violated. The NT contrast is Christ&#8217;s warning: &lsquo;Do not lay up for yourselves treasures on earth, where moth and rust destroy&rsquo; (Matt 6:19). What Ahab built will not outlast judgment.</p>",
"40": "<p>Ahab sleeps with his fathers; his son Ahaziah reigns in his place. The succession formula &#8212; the king dies, the son reigns &#8212; continues the northern dynasty even as the prophetic verdict stands. The Davidic covenant&#8217;s hope rests on the southern line, not on this northern succession. But the continuation of the northern dynasty is not merely political: it is the continuation of the sin pattern that will culminate in the Assyrian exile. Dynasties without covenant faithfulness perpetuate their own judgment.</p>",
"41": "<p>Jehoshaphat the son of Asa begins to reign over Judah in the fourth year of Ahab. The parallel regnal notice &#8212; immediately after Ahab&#8217;s death &#8212; contrasts the two kingdoms. Jehoshaphat is the Davidic covenant king; his narrative is measured against the standard of his father David. The southern kings are evaluated according to the covenant; the northern kings according to the sin of Jeroboam. The two evaluative frameworks reveal the two covenant trajectories: one oriented toward the messianic fulfillment, one moving away from it.</p>",
"42": "<p>Jehoshaphat reigns twenty-five years in Jerusalem; his mother&#8217;s name is Azubah the daughter of Shilhi. The regnal formula includes the queen mother&#8217;s name &#8212; a consistent feature of Judahite succession that reflects the queen mother&#8217;s formal role in the Davidic court. The lineage through the mother is noted because it is part of the covenant succession record. In the genealogy of the Messiah (Matt 1), several women are similarly named because their inclusion in the line is theologically significant.</p>",
"43": "<p>Jehoshaphat walked in all the way of his father Asa; he did not turn aside from it, doing what was right in the sight of YHWH. Yet the high places were not taken away; the people still sacrificed and made offerings on the high places. The partial reform &#8212; covenantal character with incomplete cultic obedience &#8212; is the standard pattern of the better Judahite kings. No human king achieves complete covenant faithfulness. The one who does what is right in YHWH&#8217;s sight perfectly &#8212; without the qualification &lsquo;but the high places were not taken away&rsquo; &#8212; is the king yet to come.</p>",
"44": "<p>Jehoshaphat made peace with the king of Israel. The alliance with the northern apostate king &#8212; for which Jehoshaphat was rebuked by Jehu ben Hanani (2 Chr 19:2) &#8212; is the shadow on his otherwise positive reign. The prophetic rebuke: &lsquo;Should you help the wicked and love those who hate YHWH?&rsquo; (2 Chr 19:2) names the theological problem with the alliance. Covenant faithfulness cannot be maintained through political solidarity with those who have abandoned the covenant.</p>",
"45": "<p>The rest of Jehoshaphat&#8217;s acts &#8212; his valor and his wars &#8212; are in the Book of Chronicles of the Kings of Judah. The archival reference maintains the two parallel record systems for the two kingdoms. The Judahite king&#8217;s record is kept separately because the covenant standard applied to him is different: he is measured against David and against the covenant&#8217;s demand for exclusive YHWH worship. The record-keeping itself is an act of covenantal accountability.</p>",
"46": "<p>Jehoshaphat also cleared from the land the remnant of the male cult prostitutes who had remained in the days of his father Asa. The progressive purification of the covenant community across generations &#8212; each king removing what the previous left &#8212; is the pattern of imperfect but genuine reform. The eschatological purification of the covenant people (Rev 21:27: &lsquo;nothing unclean will ever enter it&rsquo;) is the goal toward which these partial purifications point, never fully achieved in the historical monarchy.</p>",
"47": "<p>There was no king in Edom; a deputy was king. The political instability of the Edomite client state &#8212; no hereditary king, only a regent &#8212; contrasts with the Davidic covenant&#8217;s promise of perpetual succession. Edom&#8217;s kinglessness is incidental; Israel&#8217;s kingship is covenantal. The contrast between the nations&#8217; political arrangements and the covenant people&#8217;s dynastic continuity reminds the reader that the Davidic throne is not just one monarchy among others but the particular vessel of redemptive history.</p>",
"48": "<p>Jehoshaphat made ships of Tarshish to go to Ophir for gold, but they did not go, for the ships were wrecked at Ezion-geber. The failed commercial venture &#8212; ambition not realized &#8212; is the counterpart to Solomon&#8217;s successful Ophir trade (1 Kgs 9:26&#8211;28). What Solomon achieved through covenant blessing, Jehoshaphat cannot replicate. The attempt to rebuild the Solomonic commercial empire without the Solomonic wisdom is the pattern of every attempted restoration that does not begin with covenant faithfulness.</p>",
"49": "<p>Ahaziah son of Ahab proposes a joint expedition to Ophir; Jehoshaphat refuses: &lsquo;I will not.&rsquo; The refusal of the alliance &#8212; in contrast to his earlier agreement to go to battle with Ahab &#8212; may reflect what Jehoshaphat learned from the Ramoth-Gilead experience. After nearly dying in a battle he entered through false alliance, he will not enter a commercial venture with the same house. Late-earned discernment is still discernment.</p>",
"50": "<p>Jehoshaphat sleeps with his fathers and is buried in the city of David his father. The burial in David&#8217;s city &#8212; the covenantal burial ground of the Davidic dynasty &#8212; is the sign of covenant succession. To rest with the fathers in the city of David is to be part of the chain of kings through whom the messianic promise passes. Each burial in the city of David is a link in the chain that leads to Christ, the ultimate Davidic heir who himself died and was buried and rose.</p>",
"51": "<p>Ahaziah the son of Ahab begins to reign over Israel in the seventeenth year of Jehoshaphat. The succession of the apostate northern dynasty &#8212; father to son &#8212; contrasts with the Davidic southern succession. Ahaziah inherits not only the throne but the pattern of his parents&#8217; covenant violations. Familial inheritance of apostasy is one of Kings&#8217; consistent themes: the sins of the fathers are visited on the children (Exod 20:5) not as unavoidable fate but as the practical outworking of a household&#8217;s formative patterns.</p>",
"52": "<p>Ahaziah did what was evil in the sight of YHWH and walked in the way of his father and mother &#8212; and in the way of Jeroboam son of Nebat. The three-generation indictment &#8212; father Ahab, mother Jezebel, founding sin of Jeroboam &#8212; situates Ahaziah at the confluence of multiple streams of apostasy. No individual is isolated from the cumulative covenantal history of their family and tradition. The NT&#8217;s concern with the &lsquo;pattern of this world&rsquo; (Rom 12:2) names the same dynamic: inherited formative patterns must be actively broken by the renewing of the mind.</p>",
"53": "<p>Ahaziah served Baal and worshipped him, and provoked YHWH the God of Israel to anger according to all that his father had done. The closing formula of the chapter &#8212; and of the entire book &#8212; returns to the beginning of the Ahab narrative&#8217;s spiritual diagnosis: Baal worship, provocation of YHWH, the continuation of the father&#8217;s sin. The book of Kings ends here in 1 Kings without resolution: the northern kingdom&#8217;s apostasy is institutionalized, the Davidic covenant tested but not broken. The resolution &#8212; the Son of David who serves no Baal and whose life provokes not wrath but the Father&#8217;s declaration of delight &#8212; awaits the New Testament.</p>"
}
}

def main():
    out_path = "data/commentary/mkt-christ/1kings.json"
    existing = load_comm(out_path)
    before_22 = len(existing.get("22", {}))
    merge_comm(existing, DATA)
    after_22 = len(existing.get("22", {}))
    save_comm(out_path, existing)
    added = after_22 - before_22
    print(f"  wrote {out_path}")
    print(f"1kings mkt-christ ch22 fill: added {added} verses (ch22: {after_22}/53)")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
